body:
Verilog ports of  data type `real` are converted to sc_signals of data type `uint64_t` in the generated SystemC module. I would have expected this to generate sc_signals of data type `double`. This of course results in the desired values being rounded to integers.

Converting the desired `double` value to `uint64_t` in `sc_main` by using `memcpy` , `reinterpret_cast`, or a union, and feeding it to the generated SystemC module results in the Verilog module seeing the raw `unsigned int` bits and not the intended `double`.

For example converting a double value of `0.8` results in an unsigned int of value `0x3FE999999999999A`.  I then pass that in as input to the generated SystemC module. Since SystemC converted the original `real` port to `uint64_t`, I would have expected it to convert my `uint64_t` value of `0x3FE999999999999A` back to a `real`. I do see this in the generated code so it knows it's supposed to be double:

```
tracep->declDouble(c+1,0,"i_VDD",-1, VerilatedTraceSigDirection::INPUT, VerilatedTraceSigKind::WIRE, VerilatedTraceSigType::DOUBLE, false,-1);
tracep->declDouble(c+3,0,"o_VDD",-1, VerilatedTraceSigDirection::OUTPUT, VerilatedTraceSigKind::WIRE, VerilatedTraceSigType::DOUBLE, false,-1);
```

Verilating to pure C++ works as expected. The generated C++ code uses `double` for the signals.

Sample Verilog module (simple.sv):
```
module simple
(
    input real i_VDD,
    output real o_VDD
);

always @(i_VDD) begin
    o_VDD <= i_VDD;
end

endmodule
```

Generated SystemC module (Vsimple.h):
```
class alignas(VL_CACHE_LINE_BYTES) Vsimple VL_NOT_FINAL : public ::sc_core::sc_module, public VerilatedModel {
  private:
    ...

  public:
    ...
    // PORTS
    // The application code writes and reads these signals to
    // propagate new values into/out from the Verilated model.
    sc_core::sc_in<uint64_t> &i_VDD;
    sc_core::sc_out<uint64_t> &o_VDD;
    ...
}
```

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?
`verilator --sc --timing --trace --top-module simple simple.sv`

`verilator --version`: Verilator 5.037 devel rev v5.036-175-g73696f0a7 (mod).
Same result with version 5.034.

What OS and distribution are you using?
Linux RedHat 8.10

May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?
I can take a stab at it, sure.

